          <h1>Environmental Radiation Protection</h1>
          <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
                face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"> <br>
              </font></font></font><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
              face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">
              <h2><span style="color: #444444;"><span style="font-family: 'Droid Sans',arial,sans-serif;">Database
                    of resuspension factors with respect to varying surface
                    roughness characteristics for CANDU reactor containment in
                    the event of a LOCA<br>
                  </span></span></h2>
              <p align="justify"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">The
                  effect of surface roughness of various surfaces on
                  resuspension of particulate and consequent theoretical
                  internal dose from inhalation is investigated. Effects of
                  roughness characteristics on resting particulate can be
                  examined by observing the sub-layer in a velocity field using
                  computational fluid dynamics and examining the cumulative
                  impact of forces on particles in 1 to 10 micron range.</font></p>
              <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">
                <p> </p>
              </font></font></font>
          <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
                  face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"> </font></font></font></p>
          <font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
                face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">
                <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">
                      <h2><span style="color: #444444;"><span style="font-family: 'Droid Sans',arial,sans-serif;">A
                            Comparison of Environmental Modelling Approaches on
                            the Case-study of the Chalk River Laboratories Site</span></span></h2>
                      <img style="width: 277px; height: 238px;" title="tracks in a pumpkinseed egg"
                        alt="" src="picturesmargarita/egg_tracks.png"><img style="width: 326px; height: 238px;"
                        title="Pumpkinseed MCNP" alt="" src="picturesmargarita/mcnpPerch.png">
                      <p><font face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
                            face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif"><font
                              face="Georgia, Times New Roman, Times, serif">Dependable
                              and fast&nbsp; assessment of radiological impact
                              on non-human biota is crucial for the nuclear
                              industry and the public. This work compares the
                              most frequently used environmental modelling
                              techniques for dose estimation in aquatic biota on
                              the practical case-study of the Chalk River
                              Laboratories Site. On the basis of water
                              concentration data the software tools RESRAD-BIOTA
                              and ERICA are and compared to the absorbed dose as
                              estimated by analytic calculation methods, the
                              point-source-distribution model and dose
                              conversion coefficients based on Monte-Carlo
                              simulations of idealized geometries. A detailed
                              MCNP dosimetric model of the studied biota is used
                              to assess the reliability of the calculation.<br>
                            </font></font></font></p>
                    </font></font> </p>
